"falls like hair,

58:23.671 --> 58:26.341
"falling across a young girl's shoulder."

58:37.769 --> 58:40.689
I'm so excited to see what you'll think.

58:43.983 --> 58:47.782
Some fresh basil.
I grew it myself on the windowsill.

58:47.862 --> 58:49.826
W-we're having pie for dinner?

58:49.906 --> 58:52.829
Yeah, but a dinner pie.

58:52.909 --> 58:54.199
Oh.

58:55.787 --> 58:58.042
What do you think's inside?

58:58.122 --> 59:00.086
Uh, inside the secret pie?

59:00.166 --> 59:03.339
Uh, I don't know. Fish?

59:03.419 --> 59:05.883
No, not fish, silly!

59:05.963 --> 59:08.636
- Want me to tell you?
- Uhh, yes, please.

59:08.716 --> 59:11.097
Okay.

59:11.177 --> 59:13.507
Cheddar cheese and Brussels sprouts.

59:15.890 --> 59:19.647
- Seriously?
- Yeah, baked into a pie.

59:19.727 --> 59:22.400
Doesn't it sound delicious?

59:22.480 --> 59:25.194
You love Brussels sprouts
and you love Cheddar cheese.

59:25.274 --> 59:28.654
I do, yeah. No, that sounds very original.

59:31.322 --> 59:33.036
Is it a new recipe you found?

59:33.116 --> 59:34.871
No, I made it up.

59:34.951 --> 59:36.748
Secret pie.

59:36.828 --> 59:38.750
I made a small one for Marvin.

59:38.830 --> 59:40.501
He really seemed to like it.

59:54.846 --> 59:59.771
Mm-hm, secret pie.

59:59.851 --> 01:00:01.981
Honey, I'm glad you like it.

01:00:05.022 --> 01:00:06.736
Speaking of secret pie,

01:00:06.816 --> 01:00:10.186
I wanted to tell you something
about your secret notebook.

01:00:11.904 --> 01:00:13.576
- What?
- Did you ever hear

01:00:13.656 --> 01:00:16.996
of the old Italian poet
called Pet-ra-rch, is that it?

01:00:17.076 --> 01:00:20.166
Mm, Petrarch. He perfected the sonnet.

01:00:20.246 --> 01:00:23.169
Um, I read online that one
of his early books of poems

01:00:23.249 --> 01:00:25.046
was called The Secret Book.

01:00:25.126 --> 01:00:26.964
Just like yours.

01:00:27.044 --> 01:00:28.508
I didn't know that.

01:00:28.588 --> 01:00:29.842
You read that?

01:00:29.922 --> 01:00:32.053
You just happened upon it online?

01:00:32.133 --> 01:00:34.722
And also that he wrote all his love poems

01:00:34.802 --> 01:00:37.183
to a beautiful girl called,

01:00:37.263 --> 01:00:39.769
ta-dah, Laura.

01:00:39.849 --> 01:00:41.187
That's true.

01:00:41.267 --> 01:00:42.772
So you have many things in common

01:00:42.852 --> 01:00:45.692
with other great and famous poets, you see.

01:00:48.191 --> 01:00:52.071
Do you like it there?
It's the waterfalls, your favourite place.

01:00:55.615 --> 01:00:57.745
I'm not sure.

01:00:57.825 --> 01:00:59.872
Yeah, it's nice there.

01:00:59.952 --> 01:01:02.667
So remember, you promised
to finally make copies

01:01:02.747 --> 01:01:04.836
of your poems this weekend.

01:01:04.916 --> 01:01:07.296
I will, as soon as I have some free time.

01:01:07.376 --> 01:01:09.215
You promised me. This weekend.

01:01:09.295 --> 01:01:11.505
I will, no, I promised.

01:01:13.424 --> 01:01:15.555
So why don't you recite me something?

01:01:15.635 --> 01:01:19.642
Just a few little lines,
maybe from the love poem.

01:01:19.722 --> 01:01:24.063
Well, I can give you
a few lines I didn't write.

01:01:24.143 --> 01:01:28.151
Are they by your hero,
Carlo William Carlos?

01:01:28.231 --> 01:01:31.070
William Carlos Williams.

01:01:31.150 --> 01:01:33.240
I know, darling. I was teasing.

01:01:36.405 --> 01:01:39.615
No, it's a poem by a... by a girl I met.

01:01:41.118 --> 01:01:42.874
A girl you met?

01:01:42.954 --> 01:01:44.208
Yeah, no, like a little girl.

01:01:44.288 --> 01:01:46.210
Like a t... like a ten-year-old girl.

01:01:46.290 --> 01:01:48.379
Oh!

01:01:48.459 --> 01:01:49.964
She was on the bus?

01:01:50.044 --> 01:01:51.883
No, I met her on my way home from work,

01:01:51.963 --> 01:01:53.843
near the old factories.

01:01:53.923 --> 01:01:58.598
She was waiting for her mom
and her sister and...

01:01:58.678 --> 01:02:00.558
and I noticed she had a notebook of poems,

01:02:00.638 --> 01:02:03.603
and she read one to me.

01:02:03.683 --> 01:02:05.353
From her own secret notebook?

01:02:07.186 --> 01:02:09.025
Yeah, exactly.

01:02:09.105 --> 01:02:11.145
The picture of the falls made me think of it.

01:02:13.442 --> 01:02:15.531
I just remember how it started.

01:02:15.611 --> 01:02:17.911
"Water falls from the bright air,

01:02:19.448 --> 01:02:20.908
"falls like hair,

01:02:22.785 --> 01:02:24.945
"falling across a young girl's shoulders."

01:02:27.498 --> 01:02:29.712
Nice.

01:02:29.792 --> 01:02:31.672
Almost like one of yours.

01:02:33.963 --> 01:02:36.677
Did she have long hair?

01:02:36.757 --> 01:02:38.763
Uh, she did, yeah.

01:02:38.843 --> 01:02:40.473
Hmm.

01:02:43.889 --> 01:02:46.938
Laura, what's all that flour and stuff for?

01:02:47.018 --> 01:02:49.732
For my cupcakes, remember?

01:02:49.812 --> 01:02:51.901
Saturday is my turn on the baking booth

01:02:51.981 --> 01:02:53.778
in the farmer's market.

01:02:53.858 --> 01:02:55.613
I remembered this morning that,
oh, my God,

01:02:55.693 --> 01:02:57.573
it's the day after tomorrow.

01:02:59.780 --> 01:03:02.700
I have so many cupcakes to make. Oh, my!

01:03:06.245 --> 01:03:08.785
- You don't like your pie?
- No, I do, yeah!

01:03:42.948 --> 01:03:45.621
Our own Romeo and Juliet.

01:03:45.701 --> 01:03:48.958
Or, maybe, more like Antony and Cleopatra?

01:03:49.038 --> 01:03:51.043
Speaking of Romeo and Juliet,

01:03:51.123 --> 01:03:52.673
Abbott and Costello.

01:03:54.043 --> 01:03:56.716
Look, Lou Costello has got to be

01:03:56.796 --> 01:03:58.718
the most famous person from Paterson.

01:03:58.798 --> 01:04:01.846
Yeah, probably, yeah. I mean, he...

01:04:01.926 --> 01:04:04.890
he's got that statue
and he's got his own park.

01:04:04.970 --> 01:04:06.892
Right, I mean,
Alexander Hamilton has a statue,

01:04:06.972 --> 01:04:10.438
others got statues but not their own park!

01:04:10.518 --> 01:04:12.690
Hell, even Fetty Wap don't have no park.

01:04:15.731 --> 01:04:17.781
Yeah, Lou Costello.

01:04:21.028 --> 01:04:22.783
I wonder where Bud Abbott was born?

01:04:22.863 --> 01:04:25.077
Uhh, that I know.

01:04:25.157 --> 01:04:26.245
Jersey, also.

01:04:26.325 --> 01:04:29.165
Asbury Park. Uh, 1895, maybe.

01:04:29.245 --> 01:04:31.334
- You knew that?
- Oh, hell, yeah, man.

01:04:31.414 --> 01:04:32.918
I know a lot of shit about a lot of shit.

01:04:34.750 --> 01:04:36.756
And Lou Costello.

01:04:36.836 --> 01:04:38.799
- "Who's on first?"
- Uh, who's on first,

01:04:38.879 --> 01:04:40.468
what's on second,

01:04:40.548 --> 01:04:43.088
- I don't know's on third...
- Wait, who's on first?

01:04:45.010 --> 01:04:47.141
Who's on first?

01:04:47.221 --> 01:04:50.019
Who's on first?

01:04:50.099 --> 01:04:51.937
I'll tell ya who's on first.

01:04:52.017 --> 01:04:54.065
And I'll tell ya what's on second too.

01:04:54.145 --> 01:04:55.941
But you ain't gonna wanna know.

01:04:56.021 --> 01:04:57.234
I can explain, sweetheart.

01:04:57.314 --> 01:04:59.695
No, let me explain.

01:04:59.775 --> 01:05:02.448
That is my cookie jar money.

01:05:02.528 --> 01:05:04.700
That is money I've been saving up

01:05:04.780 --> 01:05:08.704
so I could get my hair fixed to
go to your damn niece's wedding.

01:05:08.784 --> 01:05:11.374
That is my money. Mine!

01:05:11.454 --> 01:05:13.501
I promise, I will replace it.

01:05:13.581 --> 01:05:17.421
I will replace it after
this weekend's chess tournament.

01:05:17.501 --> 01:05:21.008
Chess tournament?

01:05:21.088 --> 01:05:24.804
Doc, you gonna need a chess tourniquet

01:05:24.884 --> 01:05:27.094
if you don't put that damn money back.

01:05:54.246 --> 01:05:55.746
You okay, Doc?

01:05:58.167 --> 01:06:01.298
Paterson, you still don't got a cell phone?

01:06:01.378 --> 01:06:03.217
Uh, no... no, I don't want one.

01:06:03.297 --> 01:06:04.468
It would be a leash.

01:06:04.548 --> 01:06:06.637
What about the better half? She got one?

01:06:06.717 --> 01:06:10.349
She's got one, yeah.
And a laptop. And an iPad.

01:06:10.429 --> 01:06:12.101
She doesn't want you to get one?

01:06:12.181 --> 01:06:18.021
No, no, she's okay about it.

01:06:20.523 --> 01:06:22.483
She understands me really well.

01:06:24.902 --> 01:06:26.862
Lucky guy.

01:06:33.160 --> 01:06:34.915
You don't listen to me at all!

01:06:34.995 --> 01:06:38.169
The friendship can be folded
into something greater.

01:06:38.249 --> 01:06:40.289
I don't want to fold it
into something greater!

01:06:44.046 --> 01:06:46.135
Hey, Doc, what d...
what does Abbott and Costello

01:06:46.215 --> 01:06:48.255
have to do with, uh, Romeo and Juliet?

01:06:49.969 --> 01:06:53.100
- Wait, wait, wait, please.
- Everett!

01:06:53.180 --> 01:06:55.140
I would rather drop dead.

01:07:16.662 --> 01:07:18.584
Is there anything we can do?

01:07:18.664 --> 01:07:22.588
Nah, I always say,
don't try to change things,

01:07:22.668 --> 01:07:25.338
or you'll make them even worse.

01:08:07.921 --> 01:08:10.511
- Good morning!
- Morning.

01:08:18.140 --> 01:08:19.895
You're up late, honey.

01:08:19.975 --> 01:08:22.606
Your silent, magic watch
didn't wake you up.

01:08:22.685 --> 01:08:25.568
Yeah, it was a little late today.

01:08:25.648 --> 01:08:29.446
Well, some days, something inside
just doesn't wanna get up.

01:08:29.526 --> 01:08:30.935
Ever feel like that?

01:08:32.696 --> 01:08:34.026
Today.

01:08:35.573 --> 01:08:38.243
Oh, my. I have so much to do.

01:08:40.245 --> 01:08:41.917
I know it's silly, but I'm so excited

01:08:41.997 --> 01:08:44.295
about the new farmer's market.

01:08:44.375 --> 01:08:47.256
Because if my cupcakes
are a big sensation,

01:08:47.336 --> 01:08:50.884
then I might be on my way
to a very successful business.

01:08:50.964 --> 01:08:54.220
That would be amazing, honey.

01:08:54.301 --> 01:08:56.140
And you know what else?

01:08:56.220 --> 01:08:58.392
My guitar should arrive today.

01:08:58.471 --> 01:09:01.812
My Harlequin guitar, direct from Esteban.

01:09:03.727 --> 01:09:07.109
Is Esteban gonna deliver it personally?

01:09:07.189 --> 01:09:08.484
Who knows?

01:09:12.111 --> 01:09:15.241
Mmm, smells good.

01:09:23.413 --> 01:09:25.334
I like your technique.

01:09:49.564 --> 01:09:51.645
The Run.

01:10:00.242 --> 01:10:03.624
I go through

01:10:03.704 --> 01:10:06.624
trillions of molecules

01:10:08.584 --> 01:10:11.131
that move aside

01:10:11.211 --> 01:10:14.131
to make way for me,

01:10:15.340 --> 01:10:18.180
while on both sides,

01:10:18.260 --> 01:10:19.600
trillions more

01:10:21.096 --> 01:10:23.386
stay where they are.

01:10:24.850 --> 01:10:27.064
The windshield wiper blade

01:10:27.144 --> 01:10:29.404
starts to squeak.

01:10:30.773 --> 01:10:32.733
The rain has stopped.

01:10:34.318 --> 01:10:35.488
I stop.

01:10:42.701 --> 01:10:44.415
Morning, Donny.

01:10:44.495 --> 01:10:45.582
You okay?

01:10:45.662 --> 01:10:47.332
No, not really.

01:10:49.666 --> 01:10:51.536
You don't even wanna know.

01:11:32.626 --> 01:11:34.673
I go through trillions of molecules

01:11:34.753 --> 01:11:36.133
that move aside

01:11:36.213 --> 01:11:37.968
to make way for me,

01:11:38.048 --> 01:11:39.511
while on both sides,

01:11:39.591 --> 01:11:41.430
trillions more

01:11:41.510 --> 01:11:44.349
stay where they are.

01:11:44.429 --> 01:11:47.519
The windshield wiper blade
starts to squeak.

01:11:49.643 --> 01:11:51.899
The rain has stopped.

01:11:51.979 --> 01:11:54.109
I stop.

01:11:54.189 --> 01:11:55.778
On the corner,

01:11:55.858 --> 01:11:58.405
a boy in a yellow raincoat

01:11:58.485 --> 01:12:00.565
holding his mother's hand.

01:14:04.945 --> 01:14:06.533
I think it's probably best if we, uh,

01:14:06.613 --> 01:14:09.620
stand as far away from the bus as we can.

01:14:09.700 --> 01:14:12.247
It's not gonna catch
on fire or anything, is it?

01:14:12.327 --> 01:14:14.291
It could explode into a fireball!

01:14:14.371 --> 01:14:16.585
Oh, no, ma'am.
It's just an electrical problem.

01:14:16.665 --> 01:14:18.295
What's gonna happen to us now?

01:14:18.375 --> 01:14:19.880
Are we stranded here?

01:14:19.960 --> 01:14:23.216
Oh, no, no, no.
Another bus will come get us shortly.

01:14:23.296 --> 01:14:25.256
Dear God.

01:14:31.888 --> 01:14:35.062
I think we'll just gather up over there,
if you don't mind, thank you very much.

01:14:35.142 --> 01:14:39.650
Okay, people. Let's join the rest
of the passengers, if we could.

01:14:39.730 --> 01:14:41.610
- Did we run out of gas?
- No, plenty of gas.

01:14:41.690 --> 01:14:44.071
It's just, uh, an electrical problem.

01:14:44.151 --> 01:14:46.865
Sabotage, probably.

01:14:46.945 --> 01:14:49.826
Okay, let's... let's come over here.

01:14:49.906 --> 01:14:51.662
Another bus will come get us in a minute.

01:14:51.742 --> 01:14:55.832
Okay everyone, I... I apologise
again for this inconvenience.

01:14:55.912 --> 01:14:57.751
I think it's best if we wait
here for a few minutes

01:14:57.831 --> 01:15:01.961
and, uh, I'll call now for a replacement bus.

01:15:07.049 --> 01:15:09.846
- Don't you have a smartphone?
- Uh, no, I don't.

01:15:09.926 --> 01:15:11.306
I don't, not with me.

01:15:11.386 --> 01:15:13.183
Would you like to use my phone,
Mr Bus Driver?

01:15:13.263 --> 01:15:15.727
Oh, if you don't mind. Thank you.

01:15:15.807 --> 01:15:17.562
So, what's gonna happen to this bus?

01:15:17.642 --> 01:15:20.732
Um, well, a... a big truck is gonna come

01:15:20.812 --> 01:15:22.275
and tow it back to the depot.

01:15:22.355 --> 01:15:24.319
- Awesome.
- Thank you very much.

01:15:24.399 --> 01:15:25.821
- I can't wait to see the truck.
- Okay, I'll just be over here.

01:15:25.901 --> 01:15:27.155
I apologise again.

01:15:42.084 --> 01:15:46.299
Hi, this is Paterson, bus 23,
I have a situation.

01:15:46.379 --> 01:15:48.010
Third, second and first.

01:15:48.090 --> 01:15:51.346
Third, second, first.

01:15:51.426 --> 01:15:53.807
Pluck all those strings together.

01:15:53.887 --> 01:15:55.177
There you have your first chord.

01:17:46.583 --> 01:17:48.880
Surprise!

01:17:48.960 --> 01:17:51.840
Just sit down, darling,
for a second, and listen to this.

01:17:53.131 --> 01:17:54.381
Okay.

01:18:05.727 --> 01:18:09.985
# I've been working on the railroad

01:18:10.065 --> 01:18:14.281
# All the livelong day

01:18:14.361 --> 01:18:18.160
# I've been working on the railroad

01:18:18.240 --> 01:18:22.490
# Just to pass the time away #

01:18:24.287 --> 01:18:27.961
Well, that's as far as I got so far.

01:18:28.041 --> 01:18:29.504
But it's pretty amazing, right?

01:18:29.584 --> 01:18:30.839
For someone who never played before?

01:18:30.919 --> 01:18:32.465
It's very amazing.

01:18:32.545 --> 01:18:34.009
You just learned all that today?

01:18:34.089 --> 01:18:37.179
Yeah, from these instructional DVDs.

01:18:37.259 --> 01:18:39.848
And I've been baking all day too.

01:18:39.928 --> 01:18:41.641
Well, I'm very impressed.

01:18:41.721 --> 01:18:43.185
Isn't she beautiful?

01:18:43.265 --> 01:18:46.021
Yeah, you two were made for each other.

01:18:46.101 --> 01:18:48.690
What's it called again? The... the Jester?

01:18:48.770 --> 01:18:51.026
- No, the Harlequin.
- Harlequin.

01:18:51.106 --> 01:18:53.016
And thank you, my love.

01:18:55.944 --> 01:18:58.742
You look a little drained.

01:18:58.822 --> 01:19:00.160
You're home a little late.

01:19:00.240 --> 01:19:02.120
Was your day okay?

01:19:02.200 --> 01:19:04.706
Well, it was until the bus broke down.

01:19:04.786 --> 01:19:07.083
The bus broke down? Was it dangerous?

01:19:07.163 --> 01:19:10.378
No, it was just, uh, just sputtered out.

01:19:10.458 --> 01:19:12.172
It was an electrical problem.

01:19:12.252 --> 01:19:14.174
Electrical problem?

01:19:14.254 --> 01:19:16.885
Could it have exploded into a fireball?

01:19:16.965 --> 01:19:19.304
No, no.

01:19:19.384 --> 01:19:21.598
It's just an old bus.

01:19:21.678 --> 01:19:23.516
Well, I think they should get
their best driver,

01:19:23.596 --> 01:19:25.727
who's also a great poet, a brand-new bus.

01:19:25.807 --> 01:19:27.103
It's the least they could do.

01:19:27.183 --> 01:19:28.897
The city of Paterson?

01:19:28.977 --> 01:19:30.347
Not likely.

01:19:31.938 --> 01:19:33.898
Well, honey. I'm just glad you're okay.

01:19:37.068 --> 01:19:38.823
Maybe you should get a smartphone.

01:19:38.903 --> 01:19:40.242
Just for emergencies.

01:19:40.322 --> 01:19:42.244
You know I don't want one.

01:19:42.324 --> 01:19:45.163
The world worked fine
before they even existed.

01:19:45.243 --> 01:19:48.503
I know, darling, but sometimes
they make things easier.

01:19:50.790 --> 01:19:52.462
Honey, since the kitchen's a mess

01:19:52.542 --> 01:19:55.131
with all my baking going on,
couldn't we order out?

01:19:55.211 --> 01:19:57.384
Like, a pizza?

01:19:57.464 --> 01:20:00.679
- Pizza's fine with me.
- Great.

01:20:00.759 --> 01:20:03.098
Then after dinner,
while you and Marvin go out,

01:20:03.178 --> 01:20:05.684
I could practise just a little more.

01:20:05.764 --> 01:20:08.184
I wanna learn the rest
of that song, at least.

01:20:29.913 --> 01:20:31.123
The Harlequin.

01:20:46.888 --> 01:20:49.269
So what'd they do?
Send a mechanic, uh, on site

01:20:49.349 --> 01:20:50.979
or tow the motherfucker or what?

01:20:51.059 --> 01:20:53.231
Yeah, yeah. They come
and tow it back to the depot,

01:20:53.311 --> 01:20:55.984
and they send a replacement bus
for the passengers.

01:20:56.064 --> 01:20:57.861
Man, that could've been a lot worse.

01:20:57.941 --> 01:21:00.405
Damn thing could've exploded
into a fuckin' fireball!

01:21:07.575 --> 01:21:09.998
Hey, Doc, if you're not
doing anything tomorrow,

01:21:10.078 --> 01:21:12.167
they're having the new outdoor
farmer's market again.

01:21:12.247 --> 01:21:14.794
And I know for a fact there's gonna be

01:21:14.874 --> 01:21:19.132
some fantastic cupcakes
for sale in the bakery booth.

01:21:19.212 --> 01:21:23.720
Oh, tomorrow's, uh... tomorrow's Saturday.

01:21:23.800 --> 01:21:26.973
I got that big chess tournament
goin' on over there in Camden.

01:21:27.053 --> 01:21:29.184
Oh, right, right.

01:21:29.264 --> 01:21:31.353
Okay, well, good luck.

01:21:31.433 --> 01:21:33.271
Yeah, thanks.

01:21:33.351 --> 01:21:34.856
Hey, fellas.

01:21:34.936 --> 01:21:36.941
- Hey, Marie.
- Hey, shortie.

01:21:37.021 --> 01:21:39.110
How you and, uh, Romeo doin'?

01:21:39.190 --> 01:21:41.196
Please, Everett!

01:21:41.276 --> 01:21:42.822
And we're not doing.

01:21:42.902 --> 01:21:44.783
If anything, he's acting worse.

01:21:44.863 --> 01:21:47.243
But I think the key word is acting.

01:21:47.323 --> 01:21:51.081
Well, how well do you really know him?

01:21:51.161 --> 01:21:52.749
We've known each other since we were kids.

01:21:52.829 --> 01:21:53.833
And I really do care about him.

01:21:53.913 --> 01:21:55.335
It's just...

01:21:55.415 --> 01:21:57.253
this whole girlfriend thing
was a big mistake.

01:21:57.333 --> 01:21:59.672
Obviously.

01:21:59.752 --> 01:22:02.217
It's cool. He just needs to act out.

01:22:02.297 --> 01:22:04.344
He's always been that way.
He needed some kind of drama,

01:22:04.424 --> 01:22:05.720
and then he gets over it.

01:22:05.800 --> 01:22:07.722
He's not gonna do anything crazy, is he?

01:22:07.802 --> 01:22:09.516
If you ask me, everything he does is crazy.

01:22:12.432 --> 01:22:14.854
Speak of the devil.

01:22:14.934 --> 01:22:17.148
Baby, I need to talk to you for a minute.

01:22:17.228 --> 01:22:19.025
Everett, why can't you
just forget about me?

01:22:19.105 --> 01:22:22.225
- Because I am in love with you.
- Well, you can't have me.

01:22:28.865 --> 01:22:30.275
Okay.

01:22:34.078 --> 01:22:35.958
Okay.

01:22:40.835 --> 01:22:43.875
Okay, then nobody move!

01:22:51.429 --> 01:22:53.935
If I can't have you, then I guess nobody can.

01:22:54.015 --> 01:22:55.437
Everett.

01:22:55.517 --> 01:22:56.855
Stop acting crazy.

01:22:56.935 --> 01:22:59.399
Crazy? You wanna see crazy?

01:22:59.479 --> 01:23:01.649
I'll show y'all crazy!

01:23:07.612 --> 01:23:09.452
Smooth move, Paterson.

01:23:15.662 --> 01:23:17.625
You damn chucklehead.

01:23:17.705 --> 01:23:19.878
Comin' in here. Clearin' out my place.

01:23:19.958 --> 01:23:23.338
I oughta kick your black ass.

01:23:39.894 --> 01:23:42.984
Without love,

01:23:43.064 --> 01:23:45.944
what reason is there for anything?

01:23:57.996 --> 01:24:00.710
Thanks, Paterson.

01:24:00.790 --> 01:24:02.962
That was very heroic.

01:24:03.042 --> 01:24:04.547
Yeah, wow. Okay.

01:24:04.627 --> 01:24:05.965
I don't know.

01:24:06.045 --> 01:24:07.800
If it wasn't for you,

01:24:07.880 --> 01:24:11.638
crazy motherfucker might have shot
himself to death with a piece of foam.

01:24:44.375 --> 01:24:45.955
Good morning.

01:24:48.921 --> 01:24:50.343
What time is it?

01:24:50.423 --> 01:24:52.883
- It's Saturday morning, baby.
- Oh.

01:24:54.719 --> 01:24:57.225
You were out a little late last night.

01:24:57.305 --> 01:25:00.144
Yeah.

01:25:00.224 --> 01:25:03.144
There was, umm...

01:25:04.604 --> 01:25:07.860
an incident at the... at the bar.

01:25:07.940 --> 01:25:11.739
Incident at the bar? What happened?

01:25:11.819 --> 01:25:13.700
Well...

01:25:13.780 --> 01:25:15.577
- Oh, a guy had a gun.
- What?

01:25:15.657 --> 01:25:17.537
Well, he had what I thought was a real gun.

01:25:17.617 --> 01:25:19.080
And he threatened this girl and...

01:25:19.160 --> 01:25:20.915
Oh, my God! He threatened a girl?

01:25:20.995 --> 01:25:22.709
He threatened to shoot himself.

01:25:22.789 --> 01:25:25.295
All because he's in love with her.

01:25:25.375 --> 01:25:28.298
It's complicated. Anyway, I tried to stop him
and I knocked the gun away

01:25:28.378 --> 01:25:30.758
and turns out it was a toy gun

01:25:30.838 --> 01:25:32.378
that shoots little foam pellets.

01:25:34.717 --> 01:25:36.639
Sure looked real, though.

01:25:36.719 --> 01:25:38.725
Oh, honey.

01:25:38.805 --> 01:25:42.020
Oh, that's so frightening.

01:25:42.100 --> 01:25:44.600
You acted so heroically.

01:25:48.523 --> 01:25:50.987
I told you that place could be dangerous.

01:25:51.067 --> 01:25:53.823
I mean, anyone could
just walk in there any time

01:25:53.903 --> 01:25:55.658
with a shotgun or something.

01:25:55.738 --> 01:25:56.951
Now you see what I mean?

01:25:57.031 --> 01:25:58.828
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

01:25:58.908 --> 01:26:01.328
But it was only... it was only a toy gun.

01:26:02.995 --> 01:26:04.751
Why are you up already?

01:26:04.831 --> 01:26:06.586
It's Saturday.

01:26:06.666 --> 01:26:09.505
I have to get my cupcakes
to the farmer's market.

01:26:09.585 --> 01:26:11.705
- Remember?
- I do now.

01:26:15.550 --> 01:26:17.430
I smell cupcakes.

01:26:25.560 --> 01:26:28.060
Mmm, still smell a hint of beer.

01:26:45.079 --> 01:26:46.459
Wow!

01:26:46.539 --> 01:26:48.753
This looks fantastic, baby.

01:26:48.833 --> 01:26:51.343
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

01:26:56.424 --> 01:26:58.763
Who's sitting in Daddy's chair?

01:26:58.843 --> 01:27:00.603
Who's sitting in Daddy's chair, huh?

01:27:04.098 --> 01:27:05.812
William Carlos Williams?

01:27:05.892 --> 01:27:08.602
Oh, no, uh, Carlo William Carlos.

01:27:11.856 --> 01:27:14.153
Will you read me that one I love so much?

01:27:14.233 --> 01:27:17.401
"This Is Just To Say"? Comin' up.

01:27:24.160 --> 01:27:25.700
"This is just to say

01:27:28.080 --> 01:27:31.671
"I have eaten the plums
that were in the icebox

01:27:31.751 --> 01:27:35.341
"and which you were probably
saving for breakfast.

01:27:35.421 --> 01:27:37.552
"Forgive me.

01:27:37.632 --> 01:27:40.346
"They were delicious,

01:27:40.426 --> 01:27:44.350
"so sweet and so cold."

01:27:44.430 --> 01:27:47.729
- Oh, I love that poem.
- Yeah, that's a good one.

01:27:47.809 --> 01:27:49.897
And some of yours are just as good.

01:27:49.977 --> 01:27:51.147
Well...

01:27:54.440 --> 01:27:56.487
Now, remember your promise.

01:27:56.567 --> 01:27:58.114
I promised.

01:27:58.194 --> 01:27:59.657
I better get going.

01:27:59.737 --> 01:28:02.368
Could you put the rest in the boxes?

01:28:02.448 --> 01:28:03.738
Sure.

01:28:25.513 --> 01:28:26.893
Okay.

01:28:26.973 --> 01:28:28.436
This is the last of 'em.

01:28:28.516 --> 01:28:29.771
- Oh, thank you. Thank you.
- Oh, wow.

01:28:29.851 --> 01:28:32.064
All together like this, they look great.

01:28:32.144 --> 01:28:35.151
- I'm so excited.
- Good.

01:28:35.231 --> 01:28:37.236
Okay, they should be good,
if you just drive slowly.

01:28:37.316 --> 01:28:38.896
Yeah, yeah. I... I will.

01:28:44.782 --> 01:28:48.748
- You're not taking him with you?
- Oh, honey, I can't.

01:28:48.828 --> 01:28:51.208
Maybe you could take him
for a walk later, huh?

01:28:52.915 --> 01:28:54.754
Love you.

01:28:54.834 --> 01:28:55.844
Yeah, love you.

01:29:15.897 --> 01:29:17.317
All right. Come on, Marvin.

01:29:37.585 --> 01:29:39.665
Come on, Marvin.
Can't we stop here for a second?

01:29:52.141 --> 01:29:54.146
Pumpkin

01:29:54.226 --> 01:29:57.024
My little pumpkin,

01:29:57.104 --> 01:30:02.494
I like to think about other girls sometimes,

01:30:03.611 --> 01:30:05.408
but

01:30:05.488 --> 01:30:07.827
the truth is

01:30:07.907 --> 01:30:11.867
if you ever left me,

01:30:15.373 --> 01:30:19.543
I'd tear my heart out

01:30:22.588 --> 01:30:25.628
and never put it back.

01:30:27.927 --> 01:30:32.257
There'll never be anyone like you.

01:30:33.933 --> 01:30:36.814
How embarrassing.

01:30:45.611 --> 01:30:47.821
- Honey?
- Down here.

01:30:52.952 --> 01:30:56.002
- How'd it go?
- Oh, honey, I'm so happy!

01:30:57.832 --> 01:31:02.089
You won't believe this, but I made $286.

01:31:02.169 --> 01:31:03.549
Wow.

01:31:03.629 --> 01:31:05.217
My cupcakes were a huge hit.

01:31:05.297 --> 01:31:06.636
Everyone's talking about them.

01:31:06.716 --> 01:31:08.346
That's fantastic.

01:31:09.677 --> 01:31:11.347
Marvin!

01:31:28.696 --> 01:31:31.702
$286 cash money, baby.

01:31:31.782 --> 01:31:33.496
Wow!

01:31:33.576 --> 01:31:36.165
I know it's no big deal.
It's just silly cupcakes.

01:31:36.245 --> 01:31:37.875
But I'm quite proud of myself.

01:31:37.955 --> 01:31:39.752
Oh, yeah, you should be.

01:31:39.832 --> 01:31:41.337
Can we celebrate?

01:31:41.417 --> 01:31:43.756
Uh, yeah, sure. What should we do?

01:31:43.836 --> 01:31:46.509
- First of all, I'm gonna treat.
- Okay.

01:31:46.589 --> 01:31:49.178
I'd like to go to dinner
and then go to the movies.

01:31:49.258 --> 01:31:52.723
We haven't gone to the movies in so long.

01:31:52.803 --> 01:31:55.351
Uh, yeah, no... no we haven't.
What should we see?

01:31:55.431 --> 01:31:57.061
You know that one theatre at the mall

01:31:57.141 --> 01:31:59.981
now shows old scary movies
on Saturday nights?

01:32:00.061 --> 01:32:01.649
We could see an old scary movie.

01:32:01.729 --> 01:32:03.484
I'm gonna get changed and get ready.

01:32:03.564 --> 01:32:04.694
I'm very proud of you.

01:32:07.151 --> 01:32:09.490
And you, my little man.

01:32:09.570 --> 01:32:12.990
You're gonna have to stay here
and guard the palace.

01:32:19.497 --> 01:32:20.577
Honey, should I change my shirt?

01:32:22.958 --> 01:32:24.788
That'd be nice.

01:32:33.469 --> 01:32:36.142
This is so much fun.

01:32:36.222 --> 01:32:39.182
It's like, you're living in the 20th century.

01:32:46.899 --> 01:32:48.863
This is Mr Parker, Lota.

01:32:48.943 --> 01:32:51.824
How do you do? Don't be afraid.

01:32:51.904 --> 01:32:53.701
How do you do?

01:32:53.781 --> 01:32:56.704
Mr Parker has come to us
from over the sea.

01:32:56.784 --> 01:32:59.081
She's a pure Polynesian.

01:32:59.161 --> 01:33:02.168
The only woman on the entire island.

01:33:02.248 --> 01:33:05.129
Well, uh, I'll leave
you two young people together.

01:33:05.209 --> 01:33:07.089
I've got work to do.

01:33:11.340 --> 01:33:12.720
Won't you sit down?

01:33:14.593 --> 01:33:16.849
You come from the sea?

01:33:16.929 --> 01:33:20.679
Well, around it.
Three days on an upturned lifeboat.

01:33:22.685 --> 01:33:25.935
- You go away?
- Tomorrow morning.

01:33:28.274 --> 01:33:30.614
I wish you would not go away.

01:33:33.320 --> 01:33:37.320
Oh, that's very nice of you, but I must.

01:33:39.368 --> 01:33:41.916
You'll come back? Again?

01:33:41.996 --> 01:33:44.496
Well, I don't know.

01:33:47.084 --> 01:33:49.965
How does it happen that you're
the only woman on this island?

01:33:50.045 --> 01:33:52.665
Did, uh, Dr Moreau bring you here?

01:33:54.550 --> 01:33:57.850
Pardon me if I seem to be too inquisitive.

01:34:00.055 --> 01:34:01.811
Quickly, please!

01:34:03.350 --> 01:34:05.060
Get out!

01:34:10.858 --> 01:34:13.239
They're vivisecting a human being.

01:34:13.319 --> 01:34:16.617
They're cutting a living man to pieces.

01:34:16.697 --> 01:34:18.317
Now I know about his natives.

01:34:19.992 --> 01:34:22.331
They're his victims.

01:34:22.411 --> 01:34:25.126
I did love it that it was in black and white.

01:34:25.206 --> 01:34:27.711
Yeah, yeah, I haven't...

01:34:27.791 --> 01:34:29.921
I haven't seen a black-and-white movie
in a long time.

01:34:32.004 --> 01:34:34.301
My favourite part was when the lead guy

01:34:34.381 --> 01:34:36.220
kissed the wild panther girl.

01:34:37.801 --> 01:34:40.224
You look... you look like her.

01:34:40.304 --> 01:34:41.814
You do. You guys could be twins.

01:34:48.103 --> 01:34:50.234
Well, thank you for treating me
to dinner and a movie.

01:34:50.314 --> 01:34:53.654
I'm happy I could.

01:34:53.734 --> 01:34:56.574
- We should do it every weekend.
- Yeah.

01:34:56.654 --> 01:35:00.077
Now that you're
the cupcake queen of Paterson.

01:35:00.157 --> 01:35:02.407
Cupcake queen of Paterson.

01:35:03.160 --> 01:35:04.707
I love it.

01:35:04.787 --> 01:35:05.867
Thank you.

01:35:18.008 --> 01:35:19.758
What is this?

01:35:21.053 --> 01:35:22.553
Marvin?

01:35:25.349 --> 01:35:28.689
Marvin, did you do this?

01:35:40.072 --> 01:35:41.869
Oh, my God!

01:35:41.949 --> 01:35:43.829
It's...

01:35:43.909 --> 01:35:45.289
It's your notebook.

01:35:48.289 --> 01:35:49.619
It's what?

01:35:51.041 --> 01:35:52.921
Your poems.

01:35:56.588 --> 01:35:58.418
Honey, I'm so sorry.

01:36:05.139 --> 01:36:08.020
I don't know what to even say.

01:36:08.100 --> 01:36:12.940
You... you usually keep your notebook
down at the basement.

01:36:15.649 --> 01:36:20.069
I guess I left it up here on the sofa.

01:36:23.532 --> 01:36:25.412
That stupid dog.

01:36:27.411 --> 01:36:29.581
He's gotta be put out in the garage.

01:37:32.267 --> 01:37:34.898
Honey, it's so early.

01:37:34.978 --> 01:37:36.558
It's Sunday.

01:37:38.315 --> 01:37:40.105
Please, come back to sleep.

01:37:43.445 --> 01:37:45.159
Please, baby.

01:37:45.239 --> 01:37:47.286
I will, I will, baby.

01:37:47.366 --> 01:37:49.326
Ye... Go back to sleep.

01:39:13.368 --> 01:39:15.538
I don't like you, Marvin.

01:39:27.049 --> 01:39:28.804
Marvin, didn't I put you in the garage?

01:39:28.884 --> 01:39:32.057
No, it's okay, I let him
back in when I went outside.

01:39:32.137 --> 01:39:34.560
No, he's going back out there!

01:39:34.640 --> 01:39:36.180
Come on, Marvin!

01:39:37.893 --> 01:39:40.441
No! You're staying out there!

01:39:55.827 --> 01:39:58.997
I wish you would have read me
some of your most recent poems.

01:40:00.582 --> 01:40:03.088
Maybe I could've remembered them.

01:40:03.168 --> 01:40:04.288
It's okay.

01:40:06.129 --> 01:40:07.459
They were just words...

01:40:10.259 --> 01:40:11.549
written on water.

01:40:13.262 --> 01:40:15.262
Baby, I'm so sorry.

01:40:18.225 --> 01:40:20.981
I saved all the pieces.

01:40:21.061 --> 01:40:24.860
Maybe, somehow, they could
be puzzled back together,

01:40:24.940 --> 01:40:27.404
with a computer programme, or something.

01:40:34.324 --> 01:40:36.414
Is there anything I can do to cheer you up?

01:40:38.870 --> 01:40:41.835
Should I play you the song
I've been learning on my guitar?

01:40:41.915 --> 01:40:44.546
Oh, no, that's okay.

01:40:44.626 --> 01:40:48.675
Th... I appreciate the offer,
just, maybe, not right now.

01:40:48.755 --> 01:40:49.755
Okay?

01:40:54.011 --> 01:40:56.642
Maybe you just wanna be left alone?

01:40:56.722 --> 01:40:58.227
Should I go out for a while?

01:40:58.307 --> 01:41:00.677
Oh, n-n-no, no. No, it's okay.

01:41:09.276 --> 01:41:12.032
Maybe I'll go out.

01:41:12.112 --> 01:41:13.492
Take a little walk.

01:42:08.794 --> 01:42:11.258
Paterson. It's you.

01:42:11.338 --> 01:42:13.258
Hello, Everett.

01:42:16.343 --> 01:42:20.100
I'm sorry about the other night.

01:42:20.180 --> 01:42:22.060
I kinda lost myself.

01:42:23.433 --> 01:42:24.813
Yeah.

01:42:27.104 --> 01:42:29.064
It's okay. Are you doing better now?

01:42:32.275 --> 01:42:34.565
Yeah, I guess so.

01:42:41.368 --> 01:42:43.624
You okay?

01:42:43.704 --> 01:42:45.626
You look a little low yourself.

01:42:45.706 --> 01:42:47.326
Yeah, yeah.

01:42:50.711 --> 01:42:52.549
I'm okay.

01:42:52.629 --> 01:42:54.968
Well, it's like they always say.

01:42:55.048 --> 01:42:58.847
"The sun still rises every mornin'
and sets every evenin'."

01:42:58.927 --> 01:43:01.757
- Always another day, right?
- Yeah.

01:43:04.933 --> 01:43:06.938
So far.

01:43:07.018 --> 01:43:08.598
So far, yeah.

01:43:12.566 --> 01:43:17.282
So, I guess I'll see you around, then.

01:43:17.362 --> 01:43:19.362
- Yeah, yeah, take care.
- Yeah, you too.

01:44:24.554 --> 01:44:26.101
Excuse me, please.

01:44:26.181 --> 01:44:28.562
Allow to sit?

01:44:28.642 --> 01:44:30.147
Uh, yeah.

01:44:30.227 --> 01:44:31.767
- Yeah, sure.
- Thank you.

01:45:15.522 --> 01:45:17.152
Excuse me.

01:45:17.232 --> 01:45:19.738
Maybe not acceptable behaviour,

01:45:19.818 --> 01:45:24.568
but may I ask if you from here,
in Paterson, New Jersey?

01:45:25.615 --> 01:45:26.995
Am I?

01:45:27.075 --> 01:45:29.748
Uh, yeah.

01:45:29.828 --> 01:45:31.368
Yes I am. I was born here.

01:45:32.622 --> 01:45:34.252
Excuse me again.

01:45:34.332 --> 01:45:38.673
But, are you knowing the great
poet, William Carlos Williams?

01:45:38.753 --> 01:45:40.633
Here in Paterson, New Jersey?

01:45:43.633 --> 01:45:47.015
Well, I'm aware of his poems.

01:45:47.095 --> 01:45:49.005
Excellent.

01:45:54.644 --> 01:45:59.984
May I ask if you too are a poet
of Paterson, New Jersey?

01:46:02.068 --> 01:46:05.448
Uh, no.

01:46:06.072 --> 01:46:07.494
No.

01:46:07.574 --> 01:46:08.874
I see.

01:46:15.332 --> 01:46:16.882
I'm a bus driver, myself.

01:46:18.335 --> 01:46:20.257
Just a bus driver.

01:46:20.337 --> 01:46:22.297
A bus driver in Paterson.

01:46:23.256 --> 01:46:24.836
Ah.

01:46:27.552 --> 01:46:29.432
This very poetic.

01:46:29.512 --> 01:46:31.017
Well, I'm not so sure 'bout that.

01:46:31.097 --> 01:46:35.480
Yes. This could be poem
by William Carlos Williams.

01:46:39.522 --> 01:46:43.864
Did you know interesting
French artist Jean Dubuffet

01:46:43.944 --> 01:46:50.245
was meteorologist on top
of Eiffel Tower, Paris, in 1922?

01:46:50.325 --> 01:46:52.873
- Very poetic.
- Yeah.

01:46:52.953 --> 01:46:55.792
Yeah, Jean Dubuffet.

01:46:55.872 --> 01:46:58.292
Yeah, he was, uh, he was a meteorologist.

01:47:00.126 --> 01:47:04.634
This I learn from poem
by your interesting poet,

01:47:04.714 --> 01:47:06.887
Frank O'Hara of New York City.

01:47:06.967 --> 01:47:09.890
Yeah, I read that, too.

01:47:09.970 --> 01:47:11.220
I like Frank O'Hara.

01:47:12.472 --> 01:47:17.230
The... the New York School.

01:47:17.310 --> 01:47:18.520
Ah ha.

01:47:28.113 --> 01:47:30.033
I guess you really like poetry, then?

01:47:31.324 --> 01:47:32.744
I breathe poetry.

01:47:37.455 --> 01:47:39.245
So, you write poetry?

01:47:39.958 --> 01:47:41.078
Yes.

01:47:44.963 --> 01:47:46.968
My notebooks.

01:47:47.048 --> 01:47:48.258
Ah, yeah.

01:47:50.343 --> 01:47:52.103
My poetry only in Japanese.

01:47:52.971 --> 01:47:54.471
No translation.

01:47:56.433 --> 01:47:58.855
Poetry in translation is like

01:47:58.935 --> 01:48:01.608
taking a shower with a raincoat on.

01:48:04.774 --> 01:48:06.284
I see what you mean.

01:48:10.196 --> 01:48:12.702
I hope this isn't, um,
inappropriate behaviour,

01:48:12.782 --> 01:48:16.289
but may I ask what you're doing
here in Paterson?

01:48:16.369 --> 01:48:19.626
I come here to see city
of your interesting poet,

01:48:19.706 --> 01:48:21.419
William Carlos Williams,

01:48:21.499 --> 01:48:25.340
who lived and make his poems
here in Paterson, New Jersey.

01:48:25.420 --> 01:48:27.676
- As you know.
- Yeah, yeah. He lived here.

01:48:27.756 --> 01:48:29.260
He was a doctor.

01:48:29.340 --> 01:48:31.096
Ah ha.

01:48:32.761 --> 01:48:34.011
"Ah ha," what?

01:48:35.555 --> 01:48:39.725
Also Allen Ginsberg is growing up here.

01:48:40.977 --> 01:48:42.597
Also Paterson, New Jersey.

01:48:43.980 --> 01:48:45.480
Yeah, that's true.

01:49:03.708 --> 01:49:05.338
I leave here tomorrow.

01:49:05.418 --> 01:49:06.923
Nice to meet you.

01:49:07.003 --> 01:49:11.761
Oh, nice to meet you. Are you...
you're going back to Tokyo?

01:49:11.841 --> 01:49:13.054
No, Osaka.

01:49:13.134 --> 01:49:16.349
Oh, Osaka. What I meant. Have a good trip.

01:49:16.429 --> 01:49:17.429
Thank you.

01:49:18.890 --> 01:49:20.730
- I'm sorry.
- Oh.

01:49:34.030 --> 01:49:35.452
A gift.

01:49:35.532 --> 01:49:37.078
A gift?

01:49:37.158 --> 01:49:39.372
Yes.

01:49:39.452 --> 01:49:43.462
Sometime empty page
present most possibilities.

01:49:50.880 --> 01:49:52.760
Thank you. That's very kind of you.

01:50:04.060 --> 01:50:05.770
Excuse me!

01:50:06.938 --> 01:50:08.818
Ah ha!

01:50:20.577 --> 01:50:22.537
Ah ha.

01:51:04.662 --> 01:51:06.582
The Line

01:51:08.249 --> 01:51:10.709
There's an old song

01:51:12.045 --> 01:51:16.803
my grandfather used to sing

01:51:16.883 --> 01:51:19.053
that has the question,

01:51:20.762 --> 01:51:25.562
"Or would you rather be a fish?"

01:51:25.642 --> 01:51:28.898
In the same song

01:51:28.978 --> 01:51:31.484
is the same question

01:51:31.564 --> 01:51:35.694
but with a mule and a pig,

01:51:37.904 --> 01:51:42.287
but the one I hear sometimes

01:51:42.367 --> 01:51:44.789
in my head

01:51:44.869 --> 01:51:48.585
is the fish one.

01:51:48.665 --> 01:51:52.165
Just that one line.

01:51:54.462 --> 01:51:57.342
Would you rather be a fish?

01:51:58.967 --> 01:52:04.057
As if the rest of the song

01:52:05.306 --> 01:52:08.226
didn't have to be there.

